[3] Emory case notes
Date: Mon 8 Dec 2014
Source: The Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/An-Ebola-doctors-return-from-the-edge-of-death/articleshow/45410146.cms


A 44-year-old physician contracted Ebola in Sierra Leone while treating Ebola patients in the government hospital in Kenema. He was evacuated to Emory University Hospital in Atlanta on 9 Sep 2014, the 3rd American with Ebola to be airlifted there from West Africa. He had a long, agonizing illness, with 40 days in the hospital... 6-foot-5 and 220 pounds before he got Ebola, he has lost 30 pounds, much of it muscle. He tires easily, but has begun a grueling physical therapy program to rebuild wasted muscles. "[He] was by far the sickest patient with Ebola virus cared for at Emory," said Dr. Jay B. Varkey, an infectious-disease specialist.

Doctors say his recovery has taught them that aggressive treatments, even life-support measures like ventilators and dialysis, can save some Ebola patients. Dr. Bruce S. Ribner, who leads the Emory team, said that until recently, the general practice was not to bother intubating Ebola patients or put them on dialysis, because if they got that sick, they were going to die. "One of the things his illness taught us was that you can get sick enough to need those interventions, and you can still walk out of the hospital," Dr. Ribner said. "I think it has sent a message to our colleagues around the world."

[The doctor] signed on with WHO -- expenses only, no pay -- and in August 2014 was in Kenema. He planned to stay 3 or 4 weeks. The experience was even more wrenching than he had imagined; there were often 60 to 80 patients, sometimes more, suspected and confirmed cases, from all over the country. They arrived day and night. Blood, stool and vomit were ever-present, though cleaners mopped with chlorine several times a day. But there were moments of grace. Mothers whose babies had died would feed children who were orphaned or alone. "Childless parents took care of parentless children," he said.

The protective gear required to enter the ward -- hoods, masks, rubber boots, goggles, double gloves, Tyvek suit -- was stifling. No one could wear it for more than an hour without becoming dangerously overheated. Dr. Crozier would go into the ward 2-3 times a day for as long he could stand it. When he came out to cool off, he would pour the sweat out of his boots...

On the morning of Sat 6 Sep 2014, during rounds on the ward, he developed a fever and a headache. He isolated himself in his hotel, hoping he had malaria. A colleague brought equipment so that he drew his own blood for an Ebola test, which tested positive. He had no idea how he had become infected. The specially prepared airplane picked him up on Mon 8 Sep 2014. He took pictures of himself during the flight as his face swelled and he broke out in a rash. He has no memory of the 3 weeks after he arrived at Emory...

Dr. Varkey, the infectious-disease specialist, said there were warning signs early on that he might become severely ill. The viral load in his blood was extremely high, more than 100 times that of the other patients Emory had treated. And he was becoming delirious, a sign of encephalitis. He developed intense diarrhea and received fluids and salts to prevent dehydration. He got steadily worse. By Fri 12 Sep 2014, he was struggling to breathe, and on Sun 14 Sep 2014, he was placed on a ventilator. A nurse who had also been infected in Kenema, Will Pooley -- whose evacuation Dr. Crozier had supervised -- flew to Emory from England and donated several units of plasma. The Ebola virus levels began dropping, but his kidneys failed, and he was connected to a dialysis machine. He had swelled up with 20 pounds of excess fluid. He had begun having abnormal heart rhythms. He was on the ventilator for 12 days, and on dialysis for 24 days.

He began to recover physically. But there were ominous signs that he might have suffered brain damage: His eyes wandered in different directions, and he took a long time to wake up when his sedation was withdrawn. "I thought we'd be discharging him to a nursing home as a cognitively impaired person," said Dr. Colleen Kraft, one of his doctors. When he finally did open his eyes at the end of September 2014, a few days after his 44th birthday, there were scar-like lesions on his retinas, and it is not clear whether they were getting better or worse.

He hopes to return to West Africa by February or March 2015 to help treat Ebola patients. Survivors are thought to be immune to the strain that infected them, so he figures he has built-in protection." There's still a great deal left to be done," he said... - more

[Byline: Denise Grady]

